text:
The modern way is flexbox on the parent — three lines:

```css
.parent {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center; /* horizontal */
  align-items: center;     /* vertical */
}
```

That centers `.parent`'s children both ways regardless of the child's size. `justify-content` works along the main axis (horizontal by default) and `align-items` along the cross axis (vertical).

A couple of useful alternatives depending on your situation:

**CSS Grid** — even shorter if the parent only holds the one thing you're centering:

```css
.parent {
  display: grid;
  place-items: center;
}
```

**Absolute positioning** — when you can't or don't want to make the parent a flex/grid container (e.g. centering over a positioned ancestor):

```css
.parent { position: relative; }
.child {
  position: absolute;
  top: 50%;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
}
```

The `translate(-50%, -50%)` shifts the child back by half its own width and height, so its center—not its top-left corner—lands at the midpoint.

For most layouts, reach for flexbox. One caveat: for the parent to center vertically, it needs an actual height — if it's only as tall as its content, there's no vertical space to distribute. Set a `height` (or `min-height: 100vh` for full-viewport centering) on the parent if things look off.
